label: specimen storage duration
definition: A data item which is a duration for which a specimen is stored before analysis.

label: specimen storage temperature
definition: A data item which is a temperature at which a specimen is stored.
example of usage: The refrigerator provided a sample storage temperature of -80 degree Celsius

label: specimen storage location
definition: A data item which indicates the location where a specimen is stored, usually of a room or freezer.
example of usage: molecular lab was recorded as the sample storage location.

label: virus transport medium

editor note: Planned Obsolescence: this term is a placeholder for a term requested in another ontology. Once the appropriate ontology term is available, this term’s identifier will be obsoleted with a “term replaced by” id of the other term.

label: sequence file name
definition: A sequence data item which is the name of a file containing molecular sequence data.
example of usage: The sequence data for "Zika virus envelope protein (E) gene, partial cds" is stored in a file named "AF372422-1.fasta".

label: contig number identifier
definition: A sequence data which specifies a particular contig in a sequence collection.
example of usage: When a new genome is sequenced, it is constructed from a series of overlapping sequences known as contigs. Each contig receives an identifier code that contains a unique numerical identifier, in addition to project and assembly information, to differentiate an individual contig from others within a squence collection.

label: genomic orientation
definition: A sequence data which is the orientation of a genomic element on a double stranded molecule.
example of usage: The "123" gene ORF is oriented in the 5' -> 3' direction on the DNA sense (coding) strand.

label: gene symbol
definition: A sequence data which is the short name of a gene typically derived from the gene name.
example of usage: gyrA

label: gene name
definition: A sequence data which is the name of a gene (typically) assigned by a person and/or according to a naming scheme.
example of usage: Gyrase A

label: breadth of coverage
definition: A data item which is the amount of a reference sequence covered by a sequence of interest.
example of usage: Eighty percent of the reference genome was covered by sequence fragments with a coverage depth of 4X; therefore, the breadth of coverage was 80% (4:5).

label: breadth of coverage percentage
definition: A data item which is breadth of coverage datum as a percentage.
example of usage: The breadth of coverage of the sequence of interest to the reference sequence was 75%.

label: breadth of coverage ratio
definition: A data item which is breadth of coverage datum as a ratio.
example of usage: The breadth of coverage of the sequence of interest to the reference sequence was 3:4.

label: sequence identity percentage
definition: A data item which is the number of matches (identical characters) in positions from an alignment of two molecular sequences as a percentage.
example of usage: The BLAST results for two sequences of interest resulted in a sequence identity of 50%; i.e. only 50% of the sequences matched in both nucleotide content and corresponding positions when performing a theoretically optimal local alignment.

label: reference database name
definition: A data item which is an identifier of a reference bioinformatics database.
example of usage: I used the NCBI reference sequence "RefSeq" database as a reference database for the identification and characterization of novel prokaryote sequences.
editor note: See editor note of http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000650

label: reference sequence
definition: A sequence data which is any sequence that is used as a basis for comparison against another sequence.
example of usage: The reference SARS-CoV-2 genome provided a basis for the design of PCR primers and probes to be utilized in SARS-CoV-2 detection.

label: accession number
definition: A unique identifier given to a sequence record to allow for tracking of different versions of that sequence record and the associated sequence over time in a single data repository.
example of usage: A sequence Accession number without a version suffix always refers to the latest version of the sequence.

label: reference sequence accession number
alternative term: reference accession | reference sequence accession identifier
definition: A centrally registered identifier symbol that specifies an individual sequence record in a public sequence repository and used as a basis for comparison against another sequence.
example of usage: The "Homo sapiens DRD2 mRNA" sequence has the NCBI reference sequence identifier NM_000795.

label: sequence length measurement datum
definition: A length measurement datum which is the number of base pairs in a sequence.
example of usage: The sequence length measurement datum for the Zika virus E protein gene (AF372422.1) is 830 bp.

label: reference sequence length measurement datum
definition: A sequence length measurement datum which describes the number of base pairs of a reference sequence.
example of usage: The sequence length measurment datum for the SARS-CoV-2 reference sequence (NC_045512.2) is 29903 bp.

label: reference gene sequence length datum
definition: A reference sequence length measurement datum which describes the number of base pairs of a gene retrieved from a reference sequence.
example of usage: The sequence length measurment datum for the SARS-CoV-2 reference sequence (NC_045512.2) ORF1ab gene (43740578) is 21289 bp.

label: reference protein sequence length datum
definition: A reference sequence length measurement datum which describes the number of positions of a reference protein.
example of usage: The sequence length measurment datum for the SARS-CoV-2 reference sequence (NC_045512.2) nps13_ZBD protein (YP_009725308.1) is 1802 bp.

label: input sequence length measurement datum
definition: A sequence length measurement datum about a input sequence being analyzed.
example of usage: 701bp

label: input gene sequence length measurement datum
editor preferred term: input gene sequence length measurement datum
definition: A sequence length measurement datum which describes the number of base pairs of a gene of interest undergoing analysis.

label: input protein sequence length measurement datum
editor preferred term: input protein sequence length measurement datum
definition: A sequence length measurement datum which describes the number of positions of a protein undergoing analysis.
example of usage: 638bp
